08127nam a22010455i 9783110766752DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107667527 a10.1515/97831107667522doi  a(DE-B1597)600261  a(OCoLC)1371574100  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090302bisacsh00aCommon Ground in First Language and Intercultural Interaction /ced. by Istvan Kecskes. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (VI, 341 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMouton Series in Pragmatics [MSP] ,x1864-6409 ;v2600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Understanding common ground -- tThe interdependence of common ground and context -- tUnderstanding common ground as a cognitive object -- tFrom laboratory to real life: Obstacles in common ground building -- tPresupposition failures and the negotiation of the common ground -- t2 Emergent common ground -- tGrounding emergent common ground: Detecting markers of emergent common ground in a YouTube discussion thread -- tCo-constructing emergent common ground: The role of the intercultural mediator -- tThe co-construction of common ground through exemplars unique to an ESL classroom -- t3 Common ground building -- tMutual knowledge and the ‘hidden common ground’: An interdisciplinary perspective on mutual understanding in intercultural communication -- tThe linguistic code as basis for common ground building in English as a foreign language -- tELF disagreement as an interactional resource for doing interculturality -- t4 Common ground in different discourses -- tWorking offline: Common ground in written discourse -- tMetapragmatic expressions as common ground builders in intercultural business communication -- tHarmony and common ground: Aikido principles for intercultural training -- tContributors to this volume -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years the traditional approach to common ground as a body of information shared between participants of a communicative process has been challenged. Taking into account not only L1 but also intercultural interactions and attempting to bring together the traditional view with the egocentrism-based view of cognitive psychologists, it has been argued that construction of common ground is a dynamic, emergent process. It is the convergence of the mental representation of shared knowledge that we activate, assumed mutual knowledge that we seek, and rapport as well as knowledge that we co-construct in the communicative process. This dynamic understanding of common ground has been applied in many research projects addressing both L1 and intercultural interactions in recent years. As a result several new elements, aspects and interpretations of common ground have been identified. Some researchers came to view common ground as one component in a complex contextual information structure. Others, analyzing intercultural interactions, pointed out the dynamism of the interplay of core common ground and emergent common ground. The book brings together researchers from different angles of pragmatics and communication to examine (i) what adjustments to the notion of common ground based on L1 communication should be made in the light of research in intercultural communication; (ii) what the relationship is between context, situation and common ground, and (iii) how relevant knowledge and content get selected for inclusion into core and emergent common ground.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aCommon Ground. 4aInterkulturelle Interaktion. 4aPragmatik. 4aSprechsituation. 4aWissensbasis. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES